14. The irreducible ontology issue

A crucial distinction remains.

A stochastic Schrödinger equation obtained by conditioning on a monitored environment can be interpreted merely as an observer’s evolving information. If the global system and field are treated only as one unitary wavefunction, then the derivation alone does not force one outcome to become uniquely real.

To make the theory a genuine single-outcome solution, one must assert that the commuting law-output process

[
Y_\alpha(t)
]

is an actual physical record—a beable—rather than only a possible observation.

The nondemolition conditions are

[
[Y_\alpha(s),Y_\beta(t)]=0
]

and

[
[Y_\alpha(s),X(t)]=0
\qquad
(s\le t)
]

for future conditioned system observables (X(t)).

Because the output algebra is commutative, it admits an ordinary classical probability representation. Belavkin’s measurement framework uses such nondemolition output algebras to formulate quantum filtering and dynamical state reduction. (arXiv)

HCARL must therefore add one explicit ontological statement:

[
\boxed{
\text{Exactly one law-field output history is physically actual.}
}
]

This is not a second collapse law. It identifies which part of the unitary dilation constitutes the classical record.

Without this statement, the construction is an open-system quantum-trajectory model.

With it, the construction is a single-outcome theory.

